newsitem.title: USA: CBOT soymeal hits 8-1/2 year high, soyoil strong.
newsitem.headline: CBOT soymeal hits 8-1/2 year high, soyoil strong.

text.p: CBOT March soymeal futures set an 8-1/2 year high for a nearby contract and old crop months ended limit up amid ideas USDA will further cut 1996-97 soybean ending stocks in Tuesday's crop report, traders said.
Analysts predicted USDA would shave 10 million to 15 million bushels off of an already tight estimate for 140 million bushels of soybeans.
The 8-1/2 year high is $282.50 per ton, above the $272.00 per ton mark touched in the week of September 23, 1988.
Contract highs were notched in the March, May, July, August and September contracts, and in January and March 1998.
The May, July and August contracts ended up the $10 per ton limit and will trade with expanded $15 limits on Tuesday.
Soyoil was also strongly higher on spillover strength from soybeans and soymeal. Funds were buyers on the day.

Volume was said to be moderate but lighter than the active pace seen last week. Traders said sellers were hard to find and few were willing to establish short positions ahead of Tuesday's crop report.
Soymeal ended $11.90 to $4.00 per ton higher with limitless March up $11.90 at $282.00. Soyoil closed 0.75 to 0.65 cent per lb higher with March up 0.73 at 26.02.
Traders said a buying pool of 500 lots remained in soymeal on the close.
Commercials were light sellers on the day with ADM said to be a seller of 200 lots March soymeal, traders said, and Cargill Inc sold 200 May soymeal.
ADM also sold 200 lots May soyoil and 150 lots July while Cargill sold 200 lots May and 250 lots July. Produce Grain sold 350 lots May, traders said.
Smith Barney was a noted buyer of soymeal on the day.
On the day, Prudential Securities bought 1,200 lots May soyoil and 150 lots July. Refco Inc bought 600 lots May.
Rosenthal Collins, USA Trading and Dean Witter each bought 400 lots May, traders said.
Soymeal volume was estimated by CBOT at 38,000 lots, above Friday's actual volume of 32,359 lots. Soyoil volume was pegged at 40,000 lots, against Friday's actual volume of 42,630 lots.
